Author: University of Minnesota PreCalculus Dept.
Reviewed/Remixed by: Doenet team

About the problem: Determine how many ways to arrange k people in a row from a group of n objects. Application of the standard formula for permutations.
This problem is randomized with k ranging from 3 to 6 and n ranging from 5 (k = 3, b = 2) to 12 (k = 6, b = 6).
The Worked Example can be hidden by commenting out the <hint> portion of the document.
*************************************************************-->


<problem>
<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="3" to="6"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="b" from="2" to="6"/>
  <math name="n" simplify>$k + $b</math>
  <math name="permutekOfN">$n!/$b!</math>
</setup>


<!--testing-->
<!-- <p>n = $n</p>
<p>k = $k</p>
<p>permutekOfN = $permutekOfN</p> -->
<!--testing-->
  
<p>From a group of <m>$n</m> people, in how many ways can <m>$k</m> people be seated in a row, from left to right?</p> 
  <p><m>\text{Number of ways to arrange people} = </m>
      
    <answer name="ans8" >
      <mathInput name="userInput"/> 
      <award name="correct" symbolicEquality simplifyOnCompare credit="1">    
        <when>
      $userInput=$permutekOfN
        </when>
      </award>
    </answer>
  </p>


